iStock Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cairo - &nbsp;An Egyptian parliamentary committee has voted to approve the transfer of two Red Sea islands to Saudi Arabia under a 2016 agreement with Riyadh.Tuesday's vote in the legislative and constitutional committee - 35 for, 8 against - is an important step toward the approval of the agreement by the full house, virtually a foregone conclusion given that an overwhelming majority of the chamber's 596 members support President Abdel-Fattah al-Sisi.The vote came on the third day of an often raucous debate by committee members, who exchanged accusations of treason and occasionally came close to blows.Egypt's government says the islands are Saudi but were placed in Egyptian custody in the 1950s for protection against a possible Israeli attack. Critics say surrendering them is an act of treason.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.